children.name: Lower Garden
description: The steeply overhanging, uber high off the deck front-side of the Meth Lab Boulder is typically the first formation to visually grab climbers off the road

Walking in from the parking lot at mile point west to east the Lower Garden "Old" Access trailhead will be encountered first. If Fight Club, Undertow or Mini-Me are your aim, head up this first scramble, passing a too-short to climb Turtle in A Half Shell on the way with its distincitve crack splitting it. If your sights are set on Boys In the Woods, The Good V3 or Angry Grandma, continue past this first scramble to where Roadside Boulder and Toilet Bowl are easily visible with an easier trail entry. Many opt for the "New" trailhead simply for ease, especially if the ground is wet at all, as the "Old" access can be muddy and slippery.

children.description: Obvious low sit start starting directly into steepness on minute holds. The angle turns to vert then low angle 1/2 way up boulder. Behind this boulder a series of caves host mystery problems.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Mention of cave could be removed to reduce impact on wildlife.

children.name: Near Meth Lab
children.description: Never been clean.

children.name: Meth Lab High-ball
children.description: A bad landing makes a short high-ball seem higher. Stand start.

children.name: Swollen Member
children.description: Lay start under contrived roof cave, slapping horizontally out and around bulge to quick mantle top-out. Difficulty simular to the physical nature of Silly Steep Mantle.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: MotorArête
children.description: Suprisingly quality steep sit start that ends too quick. Transitioning from steep to slab is one interesting set of holds.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Motorhead
children.description: Primary line, taking on the overhung face, avoiding the arête of MotorArête. Landing sucks.
children.transcription-notes: Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: MotorMouth
children.description: Stand start on downhill slide to Swollen Member the problem has amazing difficulty for a more generous angle of the boulder, due to not so positive holds.

children.name: Next to the Good V3
children.description: Squaty sit start with obvious holds coming out of small cave. Difficulty doesn't necessarily ease with angle. Low angle top-out finish completed by pinching arête.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Unclear what is meant by V3+/-, will be simplified to V3.

children.name: The Good V3
children.description: High quality test-piece! Stand into large matching jug, walking dimes to set up a high reach with the left hand. Matching and balancing out, the feet come up to set up one more simular high reach, this time to a smaller cruxier hold. This high dishy sloper unlocks the end top-out sequence. Classic!
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Early Exit
children.description: Shared start with The Good V3. Beyond 1st crux, a reach out right reveals a wrong-way jug. Slowly hedging into the jug unlocks an easier second crux and quicker top-out.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Another V3
children.description: Rarely cleaned, this companion to The Good V3 suffers the same foothold breaking issues that The Good V3 suffers, resulting in variance to difficulty over the years.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Cookie Monster
children.description: Kid's problem. Easy beyond easy warm-up.
children.transcription-notes: Minor grammar error assumed and corrected.

children.name: Abby Caddaby
children.description: Kid's problem. Easy beyond easy warm-up.
children.transcription-notes: Minor grammar error assumed and corrected.

children.name: Spot Me Elmo
children.description: Kid's problem. Easy beyond easy warm-up.
children.transcription-notes: Minor grammar error assumed and corrected.

children.name: The Orb
children.description: The tucked in problem is accessed by scrambling into cave below hanging boulder with large obvious Orb hold visible from the trail. A matched start on positive holds below the Orb hold quickly has you steep to start. Matching into the Orb hold, brings the feet high for a reach to the lip. Mantle top-out.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Cave route could be removed to reduce impact on wildlife.

children.name: Baldinator
children.description: Squat start or awkward sit start into decent holds, the right finding holds outside of the crack. Veering left with the crack system, this problem involves decent handholds with dime feet. Once the feet gain the crack difficulty eases through top-out.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Frontside Baldo
children.description: Sit start with options for holds. By the time holds get limited the angle is eased.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Baldo Sit
children.description: Slightly downhill an obvious low start tackles the steep downhill arête not blocked by trees.

children.name: Dan Dee's Phishing Buddy
children.description: The one exposed flank of the boulder not blocked by trees or other boulders offers a quality sit start through physical moves on semi-positive holds. Horrible landing.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Dan Dee's Roof
children.description: Angle of kicker bloc makes for awkward sit start. Handholds just above break transition to blocky set of jugs just under roof. From jugs veer right and out steep roof with holds on arête. Top-out comes after mantling lip of roof. Scary mantle.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Dan Dee's Arête
children.description: Sit start, work up the arête via positive holds on either side. Angle eases for top-out.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Not So Hueco
children.description: Sit start has a smaller cave to slide into than Yellowbottom, Hueco Wabo or Hueco Project. Can be stood into as well, this problem follows crimps, edges and cruxy holds avoiding the relief of the large ledge and jugs of A Cruel Dance.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: A Cruel Dance
children.description: Sit start veering right for obvious ledge with positive mantle where problem's steepness ends. Low angle above is reasonable when cleaned of moss, which is rare.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. ID referenced to self, unclear what was intended and left out.

children.name: Yellowbottom
children.description: Sit start out of lowest cave, making tenuous moves over worst of landings to connect with positive bulge and ledge implemented in A Cruel Dance. Minus poor landing bloc this problem would be a gem.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Hueco Wabo
children.description: Sit start in large lower cave with series of huecos, underclinging slopers and pinches. The line of holds running up the just over vert wall seems to run short on holds, but edges and crimps link to a lower angle arête top-out.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Hueco Project
children.description: Simular sit start to A Cruel Dance slid over climber's right a set of holds, this line quickly runs out of holds on a blank vert wall. The landing is quite reasonable for the Garden.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Hueco Warm-Up Left
children.description: Sit start with positive holds. Few moves from sit to mantle.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Hueco Warm-Up Right
children.description: Sit start, short like Hueco Warm-Up Left. Look for dish hidden under horizontal crack.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Big Slab
children.description: Large stand into slab with decent landings. Moss perpetually sets in. Top offers great views of area.
children.history: During lat 90's - early 2000's this slab managed to stay clean and climbable.
children.transcription-notes: Historical context separated.

children.name: Tree Slab
children.description: Divots, shallow pockets and edges, simular to Big Slab. If cleaned, this large slab offers many variants and alternative practice problems.
children.transcription-notes: Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Pockets
children.description: Awkward sit start or squat into first set of pockets. Angle immediately slabs, so once the second and third set of pockets are gained difficulty eases. Avoid crack to climber's right.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Minor grammar error assumed and corrected.

children.name: All Berned Up
children.description: Quality test-piece! Almost dead horizontal knife edge flake peppered with minor holds on both sides. Feet are present on both sides of flake. This line has seen few sends. When facing this problem, your back is the Big Boulders Shed-Off.

children.name: Obie
children.description: A rise uphill in the landing prevents sit start, stand into good holds. Veering slightly right to the distinctive jug matched on Bruno can be reached with the right, unlocking top-out.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Bruno
children.description: Sit start powering to and past distinctive large positive hold. Center flank of wall with no arête relief.
children.usable-description: Sit start powering to and past distinctive large positive hold visible in photo. Center flank of wall with no arête relief.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Ommited mention of topo from usable description in absence of photo.

children.name: Classique
children.description: Quality line. The right arête hosts quality holds with a fun and not-so awkward sit start. The landing will feel claustrophobic with the V10 Cave at your back.

children.name: Crazy Cool Arête
children.description: Isolated bloc. Sit start wrapped around the arête. Doable moves on precise, less than positive holds. Veer slightly left away from arête for top-out.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Sharma Cave
children.description: Steep pure line starting low in cave, containing many moves and parts, eventually topping out high over bad landing. Interesting holds in a cave that rarely gets wet or mossy.

children.name: Chunk Under Big's Crazy Cave and Off-Vert Wall
children.description: No climbs have been reported for this chunk.

children.name: Sometimes a Great Motion
children.description: A quality line, exceptional for its grade, tucked between the Off-Vert section and Crazy (Steep) Cave of Big Boulder. At halfway mark and above interesting holds for every move! Being in transitional area the landing is much less than desirable.

children.name: Big Stem
children.description: A quality line tucked between the more obvious Sometimes A Great Motion and Mini-Hydrotube. Sit start moves through cruxy handholds and smears until a set of stems unlocks the first of many positive holds are met. These positive holds connect to an easy top-out.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Mini-Hydrotube
children.description: Unlike Flagstone's Hydrotube this line gets lots of moss re-growth due to water line, and has big obvious holds. Sit start can seem awkward because angle's less than steep. When cleaned, holds are positive.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Eric and Ed Probably Did it
children.description: Difficulty project line, tackling a steep line of small holds to the left side of the cave. Sit start committing to only v-difficult holds, avoiding crack system of Becky's Roof Start.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Becky's Roof Start
children.description: Standing start stemming the cave, blending overhead jams and hand-holds. Once angle eases difficulty is done.
children.history: Around the corner from Becky's Roof Start and before "The Shed Off" there lies two sit starts, to full lines that have been cleaned in the past by the author. Coinciding with this cleaning of said projects the author discovered the Druid Stons. These lines were never sent, see Druid Stones guidebook.

children.name: Off Vert Wall Warm-Up
children.description: Sit start utilizing some of the only positive holds on Big. Great way to access top for cleaning / top-roping.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Slopodon Milošević
children.description: Left to right or right to left, this traverse maintains with feet less than 5 feet off the deck, controlling semi-low angle movement through a series of sloper holds, smears for feet with only the occasional pinch or divot for rest. Cruxy transitioning in and out of Francois' Arête. Many variant ways of going about traverse including slight variations on height.
children.transcription-notes: Mentioned twice with multiple IDs. Routes mentioned twice contradict with this ID.

children.name: O Trice
children.description: Walking into holds of Slopodon extending into full vertical line. Angle eases at 11 feet height with positive holds for transition. High-ball, can be top roped with Family Affair tree. Crux in first 10 feet.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Routes mentioned twice contradict with this ID.

children.name: Joey
children.description: Starts with O Trice's stand start, veering drastic right into Shake It Out following opening crux. Follows bulge.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Route ID replaced with route name. Routes mentioned twice contradict with this ID.

children.name: Shake It Out
children.description: Simular in nature to O Trice and Joey, but with some of the more positive holds, especially at 8-10 feet height.
children.transcription-notes: Route ID replaced with route name. Routes mentioned twice contradict with this ID.

children.name: Got Some Teeth
children.description: While the angle lends more positively than O Trice, Joey and Shake It Out, the holds tend to be smaller, sharper and cruxier and an otherwise simular slab.
children.transcription-notes: Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Family Affair
children.description: Big low angle slab on the corner of Big Fred facing Angry Grandma.
children.history: In 2005-2006 a family man from Salem established an anchor on tree sprouting out of Big Fred and cleaned this slab completely for top-roping with his kids. This opened up a series of low angle routes on this easiest side of Fred's. Tat is likely still present on anchor tree.
children.transcription-notes: Historical context separated.

children.name: Backside Baldo
children.description: Quality gem, tucked in an odd corner of Big Fred. Sit start on positive holds links to less positive intermediate holds verring right up the arête. A positive hold a few moves in allows for stiff mantle onto ease of Family Affair Slab. Top-out is big, and difficulty eases beyond mantle to slab.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Backside
children.description: Scrambling uphill from The Good V3, Ed's Arête is the first thing in view. Heading left at this fork puts you at Azain Crack Side, veering right continues onto Big Fred, Angry Grandma or the Hula Side of Azain.

children.name: Ed's Arête
children.description: Quality test-piece. Brilliant climbing on thin edges, smears, dimes, all the works of an ultra-intense just off-vert wall. With height comes more positive holds, but the lower portions offer variants, eliminates and traverses abound.

children.name: Wash the Dishes
children.description: Stand start, tucked between Ed's Arête and Picking-Pockets. Low, simular holds and difficult to Ed's but handholds are slightly more positive, with more positive-ness up high.

children.name: Picking-Pockets
children.description: Stand into edges and crimps, only to be greeted with ultra positive pockets, jugs and a left veering seem. Staying with thin seam or not, top-out will continue on positive holds.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Mentioned twice with multiple IDs.

children.name: Kill Your Heros
children.description: Only poor landing on the wall, with blocs below. This stand start splits the difference between the well-defined Azain Crack and Picking-Pockets.
children.transcription-notes: Mentioned twice with multiple IDs.

children.name: Azain Crack
children.description: Area standard. Quality bouldering moves from a stand start into a crack offering slick jams and holds that disappear. Beyond crack positive holds, and alternative thinner seams pick up. This climb, despite its recent bolting (along with the end of Big Fred) can be protected on natural gear (i.e. nuts and cams). Bolt(s) can be found on top as an alternative to small trees for anchoring.

children.name: Into the Light
children.description: Subterranean cave problem 6 or 7 feet climbs left and below Azain Crack. 5.5 climbing to get in and out of the cave. The problem tackles an obvious overhang with quality Garden Faire: Crimps, edges, divots, etc... Beware of critters, glass and waste. If cave exploring is the goal, a set of caves on the opposite side of Azain, uphill of Meth Lab are much more interesting for exploring and host boulder problems as well.
children.transcription-notes: Cave route could be removed to reduce impact on wildlife. Routes mentioned twice contradict with this ID. Mentioned twice with multiple IDs.

children.name: Mauritania
children.description: Standing into easier angle and holds than neighboring Ed's Arête, this line can top-out Azain or veer slightly right after intial crux to utilize the false top of Blues From Down Here and Staring at the Sun.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Route ID replaced with route name. Azain mispelled and corrected.

children.name: Blues From Down Here
children.description: This low angle portion of Azain offers a false top-out 11 feet off the deck. From this ledge climbing can continue on lower angle up to Azain's top and bolts for Crack and road-facing flank of Azain. Other than being approachable in its grade this problem stands out little.
children.transcription-notes: Azain mispelled and corrected.

children.name: Staring at the Sun
children.description: Simular to Blues form Down Here, with different holds. A distinct pocket makes for a great set-up hold. This line ends closer to small shrub.
children.transcription-notes: Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Hula Slab
children.description: Wandering path of least resistance up larger tier of big slab. Functional in setting up top-rope, although walking around via Gumby Slab may be easier. If the entire slab was clean, wouldn't be bad for top-roping ease.

children.name: Hula Chimney
children.description: Mossy off-width climbing, starting with extremely wide body stemming, the crack eventually chokes down. This cave will connect into other Azain Caves.
children.transcription-notes: Azain mispelled and corrected. Mention of cave could be removed to reduce impact on wildlife.

children.name: Hula
children.description: Quality test-piece! Great moves and holds from a low sit start to hair-raising high-ball top-out! Low starting around a corner below right arête a powerful butt start veers left to long reaches for positive 5 finger edges. Balancing out following big moves can be early crux, folowed by a series of two deadpoints / dynos veering slightly back right. After the second move, eye down the arête. Once positive holds are established on the arête difficulty eases. Tall but manageable top-out can be pre-rehearsed utilizing a top-rope. Many hop down from arête especially if moss is present, as the top-out is rarely scrubbed up after 2005.
children.history: Ground zero for the 90's bouldering movement of the Garden.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Historical context separated.

children.name: Psychodork
children.description: Great problem with iffy landing. not as bad as the neighboring Oregon Arête for landings, but the lack of space below Psychodork is less than desirable. Potential sit start would be harder than the 4+/5- destinction. Stand start stretched hand to hand, stepping into dimes. On edge moves straight up the arête finish shared with Hula on the flip side.

children.name: Oregon Arête
children.description: Beyond aesthetics, whether sit started or stood into, this problem is excellent, expect its landing. Not only does a large ground boulder block passage into the Full Stroke Cave, it is the landing for the Oregon Arête. Without poor landing this problem would be cleaned and climbed constantly, classic!
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Eskimo Roll
children.description: Head high holds are mcuh easier to transition into via Full Stroke's start, a la Dog Paddle problem Oregon Arête. Sit start and end of this focused problem, avoiding Oregon Arête and Full Stroke makes for extreme end difficulty. Rarely cleaned of moss, versus Full Stroke stays clean from frequent traffic.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Full Stroke
children.description: Quality test-piece at an extremely reasonable grade. Sit start on positive jug holds, sticking your feet into often soacked water drainage crack. A powerful deadpoint with the left gains a large, sharp open handed jug. Locking this off moves the feet higher into the crack to a foot jam. This jam, with the jug gains a right hand jug veering right. Rest, one more big move horizontally right gains another positive monkey hang jug. Either jump down from here or stem into positive feet and finish the easy but often dirty and mossy top-out.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Dog Paddle
children.description: Start into Full Stroke's sit start and first move. Veer left into intermediate holds of Eskimo Roll finishing with Oregon Arête's top-out. Can seem contrived but is a good transition towards sending Eskimo Roll, gaining familiarity with holds.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: 2 Pad Start
children.description: Obscure, but high quality and often climbed. Large portion of the cave presents rediculously steep and hold-less terrain. In the middle of this, 6-7 feet off the deck a set of starting holds present! Stacking two to three pads can access the stand start, kicking into dime feet and edges and powering through sheer vert above the steepness. The top-out is rarely completely clear of moss.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: The Other Bernd V10
children.description: Flank of rock left of crack. Obvious feet and hand holds are also obviously unusable to the mortal boulderer. Impressive aesthetic line with rails of slopers and only minute edges and crimps present. May or may not top-out through face moves, may traverse into Soule Did It to walk-off.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Soule Did It Off Width
children.description: Misplaced Moolack cruz! Wide crack with stacked fists, hips and elbows. It's all in, chicken wings, knee bars - whatever odd twist of your limbs that make it work. Try and have fun, and if you do - you're weird. (See Moolack Guide, join us in off-width weirdness).

children.name: Godfry's Grovel Roof
children.description: Classic! Steep sit start on positive fun holds heading slightly right, then back left to hook up with distinct corner holds on arête below grovel roof. Crux begins once gaston corner is gained, with controlled power moves with small feet to gain sloper lip. Top-out mantle involving slopey lip. Many find the start of this problem very user friendly, only to get shut down as angle verts and holds loose positivity.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Bag of Tricks
children.description: Fun! Start on Godfry's sit start, gaining positive ledge two moves in. Instead of veering left into Godfry's crux, veer right into positive holds traversing right. The ledge gains Azain's Gumby Slab. An undercling at knee height, or high reach for positive incut jug is two ways of going about the transition onto the slab. Once on Gumby Slab, the natural inclination is to top-out on Gumby Mantle.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Azain mispelled and corrected.

children.name: Gumby Arête
children.description: Low sit start utilizing undercling to connect positive holds to jug. From jug, tenuous slab top-out that is rarely cleaned of moss. If not clean, it is possible to transition onto Gumby Slab to top-out.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Gumby Slab
children.description: Standing into slab, picking between a handful of holds, a large positive ledge with jugs is quickly met. mantling this ledge sets up a choice of top-outs - veering left or right. Ledge can complicate a fall from above, commit and finish top-out or jump down from mid-ledge.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Gumby Crack
children.description: The fun for this climb starts after the easy sit start and low power moves in the crack. At half height a top-out slab section offers a more difficult section.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Slopey Sally
children.description: Rarely cleaned thoroughly in 2009, this entire slab is broken up by a large horizontal crack, making everything easy. Eliminating the crack creates difficulty. Top portion through a series of interesting slopers is better served without the crack.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Eric and Ed Did It
children.description: Oregon's mossy Atari! Sit start wrestling both sides of the arête on tweeky holds. Uber steep, with dynamic moves for some. Top-out can end lower than the entire Azain formation with a flat ending 12-14 feet off. Landing is bad, but not the Garden's worst.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Azain mispelled and corrected.

children.name: Bat Cave T/R Left
children.description: Top-roping the inner left mouth of the Bat Cave is met with large feature holds with big movement between. Very exciting climbing. Careful on falls, for swings into alternate side of cave.
children.transcription-notes: Cave route could be removed to reduce impact on wildlife.

children.name: Bat Cave T/R Right
children.description: Simular to the Left, alternate side of the mouth. Rappelling this entire line dumps you into the Into The Light cave.
children.transcription-notes: Route ID replaced with route name. Cave route could be removed to reduce impact on wildlife.

children.name: Spire Sit-Down
children.description: Sit start through minor steep portion or Spire. Eases after bulge.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Snakes and Martyrs
children.description: Warm-up on the Spire. Not a very tall spire, great opportunity to use interesting Garden holds on low angle.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Soul Wars
children.description: Simular to Snakes and Martyrs but different holds, and worse landing.
children.transcription-notes: Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Chockstone High-ball
children.description: Quality high-ball test-piece for its grade! Quality holds! Exhilarating finish! Sit start in cave portion of boulder directly below large roof.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Chockstone Crack
children.description: Dirty. Holds and jams are easy. Can be helpful to clean holds for Chockstone High-ball.
children.transcription-notes: Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Chockstone Arête Steep
children.description: Quality problem with worst landing. Steep sit start veering left through powerful moves from start. Stemming end eases difficulty of 2nd crux.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Chockstone Arête Slab
children.description: Stand starting into corner offers most difficulty of Chockstone Slab. Some holds tricky, but climbing maintains ease.

children.name: We Own The Sky
children.description: Stem problem, with pillar of Chockstone Arête Slab to the left and positivity to the right.
children.transcription-notes: Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Midnight City
children.description: Low angle slab with positive holds galore.

children.name: Audience of One
children.description: Route runs right of Midnight City.
children.transcription-notes: Devoid of a description, assumed from topo. Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Angus
children.description: Route runs further right of Midnight City.
children.transcription-notes: Devoid of a description, assumed from topo. Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Pelton Problem
children.description: Decent problem. On the Gumby Slab side of Chockstone High-ball, this problem is easily overlooked. Squatty sit start into interesting holds. Holding body tension is only crux.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Unsure what is meant by V1+/-, will be simplified to V1.

children.name: Grandma Ridge
children.description: Stand start into easy ridge climbing with positivity of top holds.

children.name: Angry Mom
children.description: Quality problem. Standing into just off dead vert wall. First good holds are halfway up. Connect to Ridge for longer top-out.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Hop on Grand-pop
children.description: Standing left of ground shrub, moving right to start over the top of it quickly accesses top vert wall shared with Angry Mom. Little for sit start, this tall problem is over danger zone.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Angry Me-Maw
children.description: Worst landing. Bulge that creates stem for Angry Grandma start can be started low as a sit start. Once bulge is tackled V1++ high-ball vert climbing over horrible landing.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Angry Grandma
children.description: High quality test-piece! Walk into stem between bulge and wall to snag edges. An early V3 crux links semi-positive holds veering drastically left. The V6 section kicks in linking powerful moves through crimpy cruxy holds at height. It is possible to top-rope with trees on backside.
children.history: The first ascent of this problem was admirably completed solo, after working with pad and spotter.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Historical context separated.

children.name: Ed's Cave
children.description: Single quality steep problem hidden in the gap between two boulders adjacent to Angry Grandma. Trail walks downhill into boulders with adequate space for sit start.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Rabid Squirrel
children.description: Facing Angry Grandma, this single line presents a quality sit start into interesting edges and slopers. Holds near top are great for lock and mantle for top-out.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Out of a Cave Azain
children.description: This "problem" climbs more like a route with its crack, length, and ability to step off at multiple points.
children.history: This boulder is adjacent to Azain Boulder hosts a series of mysterious caves that have a history of bouldering problems, with little information known about them.
children.transcription-notes: Azain mispelled and corrected. Cave route could be removed to reduce impact on wildlife. Historical context separated.

children.name: Blubonic Plague
children.transcription-notes: Not given ID, instead given "%%".

children.name: Blubonic Plague
children.description: Low sit start through mid-boulder to great incut slopers for mantle top-out.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Not given ID, instead given "%%".

children.name: The All or Nothing Days
children.description: Small holds broken up by the occasional positivity and small ledge. Stand into lie-backing small seam crack, this crack will disappear as angle eases towards top-out.
children.transcription-notes: Mentioned with conflicted ID on non-labeled page.

children.name: Seams High
children.description: Sit start off small pocks, divots, pockets and edges. The seam crack on this line won't pick up until 3/4 height or taller.
children.transcription-notes: Mentioned with conflicted ID on non-labeled page.

children.name: Young Dumb and Full of Rum
children.description: More dead-vert high-ball climbing on minor holds. Small seam crack towards top yields largest holds.
children.transcription-notes: Mentioned with conflicted ID on non-labeled page.

children.name: Cracked Lump
description: While there is a minor parking lot opposite the MS 300 entry ramp, getting away from this hairpin turn at one of the larger more visible parking lots further up-road or meters back adjacent to the river is advised. It is not advised to jeopardize access to the Garden by parking at the Illegal Parking lot on MS 300. It is indeed convenient to Big Fred, Azain, and Angry Grandma. And, as a walk-in this access still retains value. Parking here is unreasonable for the distance saved versus the consequence of losing climbing access to the Garden's many areas. En route to this acess point you will walk by Weigh Stop and Illegal Parking Wall. At the top of the sharp turn making the Lower Garden Access is the highly visable Illegal Parking Boulders: On the Yellow Brick Road, Oz and Off To See the Wizard. From here its uphill for a stretch before the extremly obvious Cracked Lump.

children.name: Cracked Lump
children.description: Not much taller than most boulders of the Garden, Cracked Lump presents a very big formation in terms of its width and girth. Its front facing slab offers easy climbing and two practice cracks. Walking to its mouth entrance the climber is faced with a large hallway, with steep rock on one side and a paralleling slab. Some choices bouldering problems are presenting in the hallway, and a single bolted line with visible top-anchor bolts can be seen from the road. A single uncharted boulder is tucked in behind the formation, hidden from the road until you have walked past the Cracked Lump formation. The forest behind and around the Cracked Lump may in fact yield more boulders. More areas await adventurers heading farther up MS 300 as well...

children.name: Middle Garden
description: Making your way to the Middle Garden you will be passing the parking lot Mile point 3.08, passing MS 210 (access road for Upper Garden) and parking at Mile point lot 3.3 or 3.4. Parking lot at 3.4 is not ideal, as it follows a sharp hair-turn, and is much smaller and less visible to on-coming logging trucks. The lot at mile 3.3 is larger, allows more space between the lot and the road and is the same walk length to Prince Alber and the entrance to the Middle Garden. Whether walking or driving, the head of Prince ALbert pokes up through the trees, with the Middle Garden Cliff-band looming over. Hop the roads ditch and scramble a hillside access in proximity to Prince ALber. A minor trail system presents around Prince ALber, but does not maintain or connect to other boulders of the Middle Garden. The Middle requires bushwhacking and in some cases boulder prep. Some boulders show signs of being climbed historically, but this area does not see the re-cleaning and coninuous climbing of the Lower Garden, or parts of the Upper.

children.name: Upper Garden
description: The earliest parking lot at mile point 3.08 is the ideal starting point for the Upper Garden. The walk from the parking lot at mile point 3.3 is no shorter and a lot less opportune. Either lots require walking a short distance uphill on the logging road MS 210. A single switchback at the entry loops around the bottom of the Uppers. 100 or so feet after the road bends back to perpendicular with the road below a minor pullout on the right hand side, and a series of large cut stumps on both sides of the road indicate the start of trailheads to the right hand side. If you've travelled MS 210 to a fork in the road you've gone too far. Where this fork is roughly close to Peter Brink's Itchy Balls Boulder, but there is no access trail and the area between the road and boulder tends to stay marshy.
children.transcription-notes: Minor grammar error assumed and corrected.

children.name: Scratch and Spliff Traverse
children.description: Longish fun traverse starting at lowest point on climber's right side of steep face. An uber positive double jug (that has felt like it would break for 7+ years) sets up a biggish but easy move to a set of face holds and jug breaks at the lip. Traversing right to left on positive holds tends to take rehearsal (but onsighted regularly), to a rest with positive cracks and holds. From here top-out requires a few reachy moves on positive holds ending with easy mantle. Traverse can be reversed, starting at rest before top-out back to start. Ending the traverse and topping out various alternative points results in the much more difficult Scratch and Spliff.

Once the feet have gained the starting hand holds, the space becomes large enough to spot properly. Three or four moves into the problem the angle drastically turns over from super steep to slab. Walking into the slab grovel and top-out can actually be deceptively difficult. While rest form the cave portion and positive holds are gained, the feet are minor and can be slick walking out the V0 finish.

children.name: Terry Baker
children.description: In cave feature made for bouldering, with decent landing and obvious holds. These obvious holds are deceivingly difficult and once the vert to slab portion is gained, minimal positivity presents.

children.name: Giant Killers
children.description: Similar cave to the opposed Terry Baker, but holds present on the upper slab, and some bottom blocs present a slightly worse landing.
children.transcription-notes: Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Pumpkin Warm-Up
children.description: At one point clean for quick warm-ups. Long mossed and debried over, a greater potential for problems exists around climber's' left and slightly downhill on the same boulder formation.
children.transcription-notes: Minor grammar error assumed and corrected.

children.name: Of Redeeming Quality
children.description: Never pursued, this line was scouted off any trail wrapping behind Pumpkin Warm-up
children.transcription-notes: Minor grammar error assumed and corrected.

children.name: The 2010 Project
children.description: Walked past for years en route to Mickey Mantle and its namesake problem, the cave of the problem was first seen dug out around 2005. It was not until late 2009, early 2010 that it visibly showed signs of someone prying off loose holds, and moss being cleared.

children.name: Clearcut High-ball
children.description: Classic tall problem that has gotten stiffer in years with the breaking off of foot-flakes at the stand start. After pulling off the not so feet happy start, a couple moves gain a large hold and ledge half-way up the boulder. Mantling this ledge is not so difficult once snagged. Above, composure progresses through V0 moves and a trusting reach for top jug for mantle finish.
children.transcription-notes: Minor grammar error assumed and corrected.

children.name: Wet Bail
children.description: Can be awkwardly started into, but typically this lower angle, hold ridden slab is mossy for a reason, it is a less than proud neighboring bail line. Because it is never clean and sometimes wet, it can be a more dangerous alternative to down-climbing or finishing Clearcut High-ball.
children.transcription-notes: Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Walked It (aka Gancho Walked it)
children.description: Sit starting low on crimps and slopers with good moves to quality jug is only half the battle. From this large positive ledge of a hold, complete slopers and light edges follow. Once feet gain the positive jug, the hold is not so severe, linking hands to feet is the problem.
children.transcription-notes: Minor grammar error assumed and corrected.

children.name: Scratch
children.description: Quality low start with technical moves through steep to vert. Ending slab has not been cleaned in years. But it is a decent VO+ stretch of slab off the deck. The low start is quality steep cave most drop off of, thus moss ensues.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Sniff
children.description: Similar to Walked It but shorter and steeper with mid-point jug making for easier less heady top-out. Low sit start can be a quality warm-up or progressive problem to sending the more difficult Scratch
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Slavov Left
children.description: Similar in style and difficulty as Slavov Problem, but taking on a slightly shorter flank climber's left of the primary problem.
children.transcription-notes: Minor grammar error assumed and corrected. Route ID replaced with route name. ID referenced to self, assuming main route.

children.name: Slavov Problem
children.description: Difficult problem with sit / squat start on small holds, linking a short roof, and low angle top-out in equally small a holds, Stand starting into the undercling offers more manageable stand start problem.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Slavov Arête
children.description: Easier than primary two face problems, but still quite difficult, as you hit the corner of Slavov Boulder, the holds present as more manageable, on a flank just as steep.

children.name: Squatty Slavov
children.description: Aside from the backside Backside Slavov, Squatty is the most approachable line on the boulder, but still retains difficulty with steep moves that may require a lot of learning and working.
children.transcription-notes: Route ID replaced with route name. ID referenced to self, assuming other warm-up route. Grade V2+/V3- will be simplified to V2/3

children.name: Backside Slavov
children.description: Opposite flank of boulder as other routes on boulder, this short wall offers a sit start to two move wonder before an easy top-out. It can be a warm-up to others of the boulder and area.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Route IDs replaced with placeholder.

children.name: Behind Gancho Project
children.description: Smaller boulder behind the larger Slavov Boulder is still a project.

children.name: Lucky Day
children.description: Short bloc offers a big cave with holds in the depths. Small holds link to larger at and past the lip for mellow top-out. Start is crux. Can be stood start at V1.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Minor grammar error assumed and corrected.

children.name: Lucky Day Stand
children.description: See Lucky Day
children.transcription-notes: Added since stand was given a suggested grade.

children.name: El Guapo
children.description: The space below offers a less low start than Lucky Day on this right side, but still offers problem.
children.transcription-notes: Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Dusty Bottoms
children.description: Arête offers positive holds on both sides from stand start to top-out. Warm-up worthy.

children.name: Ned Nederlander
children.description: Short sit start through few moves to easy mantle top-out on positive holds. A fall puts your back into Dusty Bottoms.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Acme
children.description: Minor holds make an otherwise VB slab slightly spicy. Can be a great warm-up with central proximity to a variety of different boulders.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Roadrunner
children.description: Start further left of Acme.
children.transcription-notes: Description not provided, so description was interpreted from topo. Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Wile E.
children.description: Attempting to corner and wrap around the arête starting off the slab offers a devious problem wanting to swing you off either side of arête

children.name: Short Stuff Crack
children.description: Short steep crack line with awkward sit start in good jams or on positive holds. Couple different ways to go about, can make for decent warm-up for Mickey.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Short Stuff Don't Fall
children.description: Short face with horrible chasm landing. Kicking into minor feet from face holds still only yields a few moves to easy mantling holds. Rarely clean, while crack stays clean from some activity.

children.name: Mickey Mantle
children.description: Classic! Starting left low squat start many years ago had a variety of foot options. Now a few dimes and smears account for the starting feet off a set of positive holds on low break. Traversing left to right for a short series of moves on small feet and semi positive sloper holds connect to positive crimps and crack pocket. From positive hand-holds, high feet quickly gain a positive jug at the lip. You can go to this jug left or right, both offer interesting next move, Once feet gain former hand break and jugs, the mantle and walk-off is mellow and is eased by difficult to see but positive foot ledges.

children.name: Mickey Direct
children.description: Shortens full Mickey by stand starting into positive jugs below lip and mantle jug. A few less minor feet and less traverse moves changes it minimally.

children.name: Pheonix Warm-Up
children.description: A few moves of easy moves with multiple options of large holds. Accounting for moss cleaning and holds breaking can make for spicy climbing when out of vogue.

children.name: Fenghuang
children.description: When cleaned, this slab line offers a bit stiffer version of its neighbors. Over time this line and others around may make for modern version of Clearcut Highball with the potential for mass hold breaking for the whole slab.

children.name: Dionysiaca
children.description: Start further right of Fenghuang.
children.transcription-notes: Description not provided, so description was interpreted from topo. Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Agenor
children.description: Start further right of Dionysiaca.
children.transcription-notes: Description not provided, so description was interpreted from topo. Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Ducks Suck
children.description: Good problem, sit start is slightly more awkward than the fluid start to Eager Beaver, but a series of underclings followed by pinches and crimps make for interesting mid to top-out. Traversing right into Eager Beaver, or finishing Ducks Suck following a start an Eager Beaver or right creates a series of varlants. Eliminates also present on this and neighboring line.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Eager Beaver
children.description: Area classic for its grade. Natural cave start sitting into positive holds. So many options for holds can create in-decision, but all points lead to positivity through semi-steep mid flank. The top-out can be devious depending on where approached. The farther right, the easier the top-out.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Dam Right, Beavers Gardened First
children.description: Despite a number of eliminates and variations to this boulder based on its plethora of holds, only this easy top-out varlant was lined and included. If you need lots of blood pumping warm-up action seek out the Eager Beaver!
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Watch Me Dude
children.description: Great problem! Area classic marred by a crippling back breaker of a base block in the event of a fall towards the top. Where neighboring problems have manageable landing, center line lands you directly on the worst of it. Beyond a difficult sit-start followed by semi-positive edges, a hard move still presents before positive holds below the lip. Once jugs are established, getting over the lip top-out isn't too difficult.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Grade V2+/V3- will be simplified to V2/3

children.name: Che'
children.description: The left flank offers a series of holds near the arête separate from Watch Me Dude, and notably more positive. Falling from helght may still land you to bad bloc below Watch Me Dude, but positive holds around the arête offer respite in case of unforeseen difficulties up high.
children.transcription-notes: Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Whipping Boy
children.description: Fairly quality line with easier sit start than Watch Me Dude, and less length between holds. A quality jug at lip sets up easy finish.
children.transcription-notes: Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Never Finished (to lip)
children.description: The cave start to positive jug after steepness was cleaned and sent in 2006, but the upper slab was left unscrubbed and unclimbed.  Some holds break in the overhang.
children.history: Likely sent 90's or previous, in 2006 the slab was left unscrubbed and unclimbed.
children.transcription-notes: Historical context separated.

children.name: Warm-Up Cave
children.description: Now mossed over, this line once offered a V0 version of Viper Room. The match jug at mid-point is suspect and may change difficult through vert portion of problem once popped loose.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Viper Room
children.description: Quality roof start out to positive holds at the lip. Vertical moves on positive holds from vert to slab through walk-off top out acts as a decent VO warm-up for the entire boulder. Crawling into the start can take some maneuvering, as it starts extremely low in the chasm. Akin to many Carver Classics, staying tight to the boulder in an extremely confined space and not allowing for body swinging turn tense moves can be as much of the crux as a particular hold or move. With space to swing this problem might seem easier.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Velvet Rope
children.description: Steep easy problem, nudging slightly right for a different sit start than Viper Room. The difference in starting holds makes this problem much more approachable. Often while Viper Room is still drying out for the season, this problem can be climbed.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: People Climb That
children.description: While I have seen this problem often cleaned, ticked and chalked, I have never witnessed or heard of a send. A stand start into upper holds isn't difficult. The cave from a lay start thropugh a few moves is manageable. But a missing link at standing height, linking said lay start to stand moves seems impractical?
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Projecto
children.description: Begins left of People Climb That
children.transcription-notes: Description not provided, so description was interpreted from topo.

children.name: Full Crack Roof
children.description: Semi-contrived, but taking advantage of any and all quality holds, from the boulders lowest point offers a fun, heady at the top problem. The midpoint crack, if utilized offers a respite to steep moves over a horrible landing with interesting knob jugs.

children.name: Jump-In
children.description: Avoiding bottom section below crack, and going right into positive jugs at the lip avoids a long traverse of a problem but tackles the headiest portion with potentially the worst section of landing for the entire problem.

children.name: Sharpen Your Teeth
children.description: Low, somewhat uncomfortable sit start with butt bloc from obvious positive hold start, a sloper at the break on the left and an opposing right hand of quality. Positive sharp pocket jug with teeth at head height sets up another positive hold along the arête out left. The jug pocket is sharp. It spit out teeth in the past but remains sharp and positive. The top-out's difficulty can be reduced by utilizing overly positive arête at top or made to be spicy by using a series of slopers and knobs on the steep corner's face.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Minor grammar error assumed and corrected.

children.name: Undercling Overbite
children.description: From Sharpen Your Teeth's start instead of continuing left after pocket, an undercling to the right sets up a series of left hand slopers. Once the highest sloper is found, a high foot brings the right to another sloper. May be stiff for its grade, but so are so many V3's at the Garden.
children.transcription-notes: Minor grammar error assumed and corrected. Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Opposite Arête
children.description: Easy sit start problem eyeing down a hold less face while lie backing the right arête. Approachable problem with chance for movement on face.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Hang and Slap
children.description: Classic. With bad bloc at your back, lay into quality starting holds and obvious edge for left foot. The right foot kicks up to dime to gain enough purchase for bigger move with the left hand, slapping for a sloper short of the arête. The next move gains the arête and easy moves ensue to walking off. Be careful for both working a bad landing for the lay start and for topping out. The landing is quite bad.
children.transcription-notes: Minor grammar error assumed and corrected.

children.name: Below Angular Staircase
children.description: Unknown.

children.name: Angular Staircase
children.description: Gets you off deck quick, but holds are super positive, from the ledges for feet to holds on both angles of the blocky corners. Big holds are good cause the landing is bad with a slight slide.

children.name: Wet Weather Days
children.description: A crawl through to the right of Angular Staircase reveals a small cave that stays dry even in the wettest of Oregon days. Physical steep undercling sit start to large holds flank the wall. One more move gains a sloper at the lip. Positive holds do easy the mantle top out, but if tackling in full weather, it's best to traverse slight right to even larger holds for top-out.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Minor grammar error assumed and corrected.

children.name: No Hold Face
children.description: As the name implies.

children.name: Sonya
children.description: Lay into cave start pure horizontal with handholds at mid-face. A few stiff moves gains the lip. From lip either top-out standard Sonya or start left or right into Out Left Sonya or Full Sonya. More options to this traverse boulder aren't presented in this guide, with various start and stop points, and multiple top-out options.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Minor grammar error assumed and corrected. Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Out Left Sonya
children.description: Standard Sonya top-out hedges slight right. Forcing a left moving traverse to corner offers quality alternative. May even transition into Sonya Slab ending.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Full Sonya
children.description: Following the crux of Sonya, instead of topping out, head right, and just keep going. Utilizing Orion's top-out goes. Continuing on to an superb long traverse finish offers a good enduro finish on the ever overhung face.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Orion
children.description: Similar to Sonya, but slightly easier as second and third set of feet dimes unfold less awkwardly.

children.name: Sonya Slab
children.description: Good warm-up to the traverse flank, a sit start is awkward while standing low into holds offers a quality problem.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Minor grammar error assumed and corrected.

children.name: Cracked Egg Roof Crack
children.description: Quality steep crack. Few moves. Can be done as a steep hold intensive problem with optional edges and pockets. As a straight in jam to jam, can be extremely quality trainer for low out sight foot jams and minor edging. Recently mossed over and trail disappeared.

children.name: Cracked Egg Face
children.description: Rarely clean, decent sit start cave face into quality positive holds through 2 lips before mantle top-out, If area wasn't so overgrown and moss didn't regrow so fast, would be quality
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Rollin' Out the Carpet
children.description: Staring in the chasm between obvious spire boulder and ground bloc broken from it. Tensioning in chasm can be part of difficulty of sit-start, as well as headiness through mid-moves above a no-fall landing. Moves are on obvious quality holds through awesome angle. Without landing, gem.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Minor grammar error assumed and corrected.

children.name: Don't Fear the Reaper
children.description: A surprisingly quality problem facing Bilbo, an obvious low cave start utilizes decent holds on obvious lip traverse from right to left. Before traversing too far into a hold-less bulge, lie-back the right side of upper bulge with feet out on the face. Decently difficult mantle top-out on slopey holds.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Minor grammar error assumed and corrected.

children.name: Hurt Locker
children.description: Opposite flank from Don't Fear the Reaper, this sit start problem ends too quickly as the steepness ends at standing height to quick top-out. A fall puts you back of a poor landing bloc.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Minor grammar error assumed and corrected.

children.name: Gimle
children.description: Visible en route to Bilbo from Sonya, this singular line on an off flank of Gandalf doesn't require topping out with a ledge before larger formations summit. Decent problem that never remains clean of moss.

children.name: Non-Crack
children.description: An obvious minor crack offering no jams, but holds littered around the seam marks a decent problem that has been known to have holds break. Gandalf's backside wall facing Bilbo and the cliff band has other options, but the rock quality is not the best.

children.name: Bilbo's Grand Traverse
children.description: Left to right, starting on vert wall squat on crimpy holds quickly hits the top lip and then proceeds to traverse around corner into steep cave, maintaining top lip holds without mantling. Once around the corner, many top-outs present, lastly easiest and furthest to Bilbo Dyno before the Pippen Boulder. Good problem with difficult in transitions. Can be reversed, starting with Hobbit Toss, then head right to left with similar cruxes and a leisurely top-out on vert extreme left.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Minor grammar error assumed and corrected.

children.name: Bilbo's Project
children.description: Capturing the climber's left corner of steep flank where traverse transitions to steep, an undone, low sit start, through interesting underclings through manageable top-out. Makes for a full line having little to do with traverse.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Minor grammar error assumed and corrected.

children.name: Hobbit Toss
children.description: Extreme right corner of cave before Pippen boulder, an obvious sit start with a big move through positive holds quickly gains lip and easy but physical mantle to top-out. Easily stuck statically, the toss move is pure fun.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Pippen
children.description: Never seen clean. Keep following Pippen around and there are two other small boulders below cliff. From Pippen a drainage on the cliff is visible.

children.name: Eye of Sauron High-ball
children.description: Scrubbed at one point to avoid loose holds high, be aware that it likely hasn't been cleaned in years. Plenty tall and a number of variant possibilities, all in the warm-up range. Landing is less than ideal with the sloping hillside and ground blocs.

children.name: Maiar High-ball
children.description: Similar to Eye of Sauron High-ball, but with an even more problematic landing
children.transcription-notes: Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Gilbert Problem
children.description: Unexpectedly quality. Low squat start heads through interesting holds and smears to the right. After a couple easier moves, one big move gains a hidden crack jug. This positive holds eases the mantle and gains a ledge end of problem. Continue onto 5.7 Crack, or walk down left.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded. Route ID replaced with route name. Minor grammar error assumed and corrected.

children.name: 5.7 Crack
children.description: Whether you shortcut in or start via the Gilbert Problem, the bomber locks and positive foot jams make this climb feasible despite the non-fall nature of the problem. Being cleaned of moss is necessary as there is no falls.
children.transcription-notes: Minor grammar error assumed and corrected.

children.name: Chepenefa
children.description: Another gem with a poor landing. A small landing is just enough space to dust off, stand starting into minor edges. Avoiding the large jug below the Arrowhead's fin bloc makes for a slightly more stiff problem, but the angle remains just at vert.

children.name: Broken Arrow
children.description: Same start as Chepenefa but allows the ultra jug below large chunk fin.
children.transcription-notes: Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Little Ben
children.description: Singular line, sit start into underclings and crimps. At vert, or less makes for ease, and a plethora of holds at lip for easy top-out.
children.transcription-notes: Abbreviation expanded.

children.name: Awesome
children.description: A less than awesome landing allows for a squat or stand start into interesting difficult holds on a sheer steep face. Unrelenting through mid and finish. Rarely cleaned.

children.name: Also Awesome
children.description: The same type of cruxy start as Awesome, but mid-problem a set of more positive holds and quality foot stances ease the end.
children.transcription-notes: Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Awesome Slab
children.description: Tall low angle corner with your right foot kicking out over the void of Awesome and Also Awesome, but with positive holds on the slab. Airy. Good. Rarely cleaned.
children.transcription-notes: Route ID replaced with route name.

children.name: Awesome Project
children.description: The primary low alcove conducive for quality steep sit start, and surprisingly hosting a nice landing is an Über hard with obvious undercling rails and knobs mid to high. Low start is tough.
